@node play "The game: Installation/Playing"

                             Installation

  The installation is very simple, just place "Permu" where you want on
your hard drive, floppy disk, Ram Disk, etc. No other files or Libraries
are needed. The only requirement is that your Workbench must have at
least 8 colours.

                             How to play?

  To play, click on any tile, except the ones in the leftmost column and
those on the uppermost row (clicking on these tiles will have no effect).
The tile you selected will exchange its position with the one located on
the upper left on the board. Also, all the tiles in the same row at the
left will permutate, the same procedure goes for all the tiles that are
located over your clicked tile.

  Here's an example of a typical game board permutation:

                   a . b .   @{b}Note@{ub}: the letters represents coloured tiles
                   . . c .         and the '.' are other tiles that are
                   . . d .         ignored in this example.
                   e f g .
                       ^
                       ^
                       Clicked tile

  The result:

                   g . d .
                   . . c .
                   . . b .
                   f e a .

  ...so the letters 'b c d', 'a g' and 'e f' changed positions
(note that the letter 'c' in the 'b c d' series didn't move
because it was located in the center of the permutation).

  Anyways, it's much more simple to play the game than it is to
explain how it works, so try it...!

  Have fun!

OPTIONS:

  You can choose the game board size by clicking on the arrows or '+' or
'-' signs, located on the upper right or lower left of the board.

  The arrows pointing up or to the right next to the '@{b}+@{ub}' sign,
are used to enlarge the board in the direction they are pointing. In
addition, the '+' sign can be used to simultaneously increase both
height and width of the board. If the board is already at its maximum
size, clicking on the '+' sign or the associated arrows will have no
effect.

  The arrows pointing down or to the left next to the '@{b}-@{ub}' sign
decrease the size of the board. Also, you can use the '-' sign to
decrease both width and height of the board, unless either the width or
height already are at their minimum.

  If you don't want to use the arrows or just want the biggest or
smallest board, you can use the '@{b}Board@{ub}' pull-down menu in where
you can choose these sizes (you can also hold Right-Amiga and '@{b}-@{ub}' or
'@{b}+@{ub}' keys for the smallest or biggest board).

  When you want to restart a game board, click on the '@{b}New Game@{ub}'
button (or in the '@{b}Game@{ub}' pull-down menu, select '@{b}New Game@{ub}', you
can also simply hold the Right-Amiga and '@{b}N@{ub}' keys).

@endnode

